Renewal under a Great Leader
London — — The Battle of Waterloo has been over for two centuries now. Napoleon's catastrophic defeat in that battle severely damaged France's self-esteem to such an extent that General Charles de Gaulle omitted any mention of it in his writing on French military history.
Nevertheless, if you consider "greatness" as a personal trait, both Napoleon and de Gaulle could be considered the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say there is no such thing as a "great leader."
From Marx's perspective, the class struggle in France created the environment that made figures like Napoleon, whom he called a "bizarre dunce," into heroes.
<p>In Tolstoy's view, Napoleon was not particularly an outstanding general; his victories should be credited to the courage and dedication of the French soldiers who won the Battle of Borodino.</p>
Regardless of whether Napoleon was great or not, we need to clarify whether we can describe any leader as great.
If the answer is yes, then who can be described as great?
Political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believes that a great leader must meet two particularly important criteria.
First, can this leader recognize the trend of history?
<p>Otto von Bismarck did so, as did his German compatriot Konrad Adenauer; drawing on Bismarck's unforgettable phrase, both heard the "rustle of the divine cloak."</p>
Second, did this leader make important decisions?
Naturally, if a leader is forced to make a decision, neither blame nor praise is warranted.
The key is whether the leader had the opportunity to weigh the pros and cons and make the right decision for the country.
De Gaulle therefore deserves a place on any list of great leaders.
<p>Almost single-handedly, he guided France out of the post-WWII backwaters.</p>
<p>After regaining power in 1958, he once again saved his country, crushing two coup attempts, ending the Algerian War, and drafting the Fifth Republic constitution.</p>
<p>Like British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, de Gaulle gave the French a new worldview, establishing their place in the post-war global order.</p>
<p>Indeed, the ultimate impact of de Gaulle and Churchill in defining their countries' worldviews was perhaps too great.</p>
<p>Their successors would continue to view the world—and the role their countries played—in ways that constrained rational discourse and distorted decision-making for years to come.</p>
<p>As a result, the leaders of the two countries since then have failed to achieve anything that can match the accomplishments of these two great leaders.</p>
<p>But there was another British Prime Minister who could be mentioned in the same breath: Margaret Thatcher, a highly controversial figure beloved by some and hated by others equally.</p>
<p>Even her resignation 25 years ago was due to rebellious activities within her own cabinet and party.</p>
<p>It is not necessary to please everyone to be a great leader.</p>
<p>In fact, even Thatcher's critics cannot deny her influence.</p>
<p>Not only did she serve as the first female prime minister of the United Kingdom and one of the earliest in other parts of the world, Thatcher helped turn around Britain's economic decline.</p>
<p>Furthermore, her offensive against overly powerful unions enhanced manageability at a time when the nation seemed to be sliding into turmoil and chaos.</p>
<p>For these reasons, she certainly qualifies as a candidate for a "great leader."</p>
<p>Similarly, while far from perfect, Deng Xiaoping of China also qualifies as a great leader.</p>
<p>Beyond aiding Mao Zedong in his wrongdoings, Deng also played a decisive role in ordering the Tiananmen massacre in 1989.</p>
<p>But Deng also liberalized the market, setting China on a path of unprecedented development and prosperity that eventually lifted hundreds of millions of Chinese out of poverty.</p>
<p>Many people consider Singapore's founder and longtime prime minister Lee Kuan Yew to be a great leader, even though he may have wished for a larger stage to demonstrate his abilities.</p>
<p>In fact, the size of a country does not seem to affect whether someone can become a great leader.</p>
<p>When I say that a small country like Luxembourg is unlikely to produce a great leader, I have no intention of being insulting, especially given the overall lack of controversy surrounding the country's political atmosphere.</p>
<p>The United States, with its vast expanse, is a likely birthplace for a great leader.</p>
Some presidents were indeed quite accomplished.
Harry Truman and Dwight Eisenhower — although not thought giants — showed remarkable judgment in establishing the postwar international order that would sustain peace for decades.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, possessed great talents — namely, the ability to inspire and the art of persuasion.
John F. Kennedy combined both strengths.
He completed a great task: defusing the Cuban Missile Crisis.
<p>He possessed an unmatched ability to inspire; in fact, his assassination only solidified the traditions he left behind.</p>
<p>In South Africa, no one has been deemed a great leader since Nelson Mandela’s death; Mandela embodied courage, authority, and a generous magnanimity.</p>
<p>In fact, he was the most charming leader I have ever met; the other two – former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former U.S. Secretary of State Colin Powell – were either African or African-American.</p>
<p>So today?</p>
<p>The only one who can claim greatness is the de facto leader of the EU, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.</p>
<p>Like Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she was often underestimated at the start but rarely made wrong decisions when it came to making important ones.</p>
<p>Kohl set the generous terms for German reunification; Merkel stood up to Putin during his invasion of Ukraine and took a宽容的态度面对移民危机。
<p>I think Marx and Tolstoy are wrong.</p>
<p>A political leader – the wielder of political power – can change the situation, for better or worse.</p>
<p>Merkel is the clearest example today, as she pointed the way for Europe to navigate the high-stakes survival crisis.</p>
